# POM Basics: Successful Login

## Concept
The **Page Object Model (POM)** is a design pattern that creates an object repository for storage of all web elements. It helps reduce code duplication and improves test maintenance. If the UI changes, you only need to update the Page Object class rather than every individual test.

## Code Example
```typescript
import { LoginPage } from './pages/LoginPage';

test('login', async ({ page }) => {
  const loginPage = new LoginPage(page);
  await loginPage.goto();
  await loginPage.login('user', 'pass');
});
```

## Real World Scenario
In a large application, the login form might be used in dozens of test files. Without POM, if the "Sign In" button ID changes, you'd have to fix every single file. With POM, you fix it once in the `LoginPage` class, and all tests are instantly repaired.

## Your Task
1. Navigate to the login page at `/app/login.html` using `loginPage.goto()`.
2. Login with username `testuser` and password `password123` using `loginPage.login()`.
3. Verify the welcome message contains "Welcome, testuser!" using `expect(page.getByRole('heading', { name: /Welcome/ })).toContainText()`.

